<p><i><b>Life of Pi</b></i> is a fantasy adventure <a href="/wiki/Novel" title="Novel">novel</a> written by <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canadian</a> author <a href="/wiki/Yann_Martel" title="Yann Martel">Yann Martel</a>. In the story, the protagonist Piscine "Pi" Molitor Patel, an <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a> boy from <a href="/wiki/Pondicherry" title="Pondicherry" class="mw-redirect">Pondicherry</a>, explores issues of <a href="/wiki/Religion" title="Religion">religion</a>, <a href="/wiki/Spirituality" title="Spirituality">spirituality</a>, and practicality from an early age. He survives 227 days after a <a href="/wiki/Shipwreck" title="Shipwreck">shipwreck</a>, while stranded on a boat in the <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Ocean" title="Pacific Ocean">Pacific Ocean</a>.</p>
<p>First published by <a href="/wiki/Knopf_Canada" title="Knopf Canada" class="mw-redirect">Knopf Canada</a> in September <a href="/wiki/2001_in_literature" title="2001 in literature">2001</a>, the UK edition of the novel won the prestigious <a href="/wiki/Man_Booker_Prize_for_Fiction" title="Man Booker Prize for Fiction" class="mw-redirect">Man Booker Prize for Fiction</a> the following year.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> It was also chosen for <a href="/wiki/CBC_Radio" title="CBC Radio">CBC Radio</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Canada_Reads" title="Canada Reads">Canada Reads</a></i> <a href="/wiki/2003_in_literature" title="2003 in literature">2003</a>, where it was championed by author Nancy Lee. It also won the 2003 <a href="/wiki/Exclusive_Books_Boeke_Prize" title="Exclusive Books Boeke Prize">Boeke Prize</a>, a South African book prize. Its <a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a> translation, <i><a href="http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Histoire_de_Pi" class="extiw" title="fr:Histoire de Pi">L'Histoire de Pi</a></i>, was also chosen in the French version of the reading competition, <i>Le combat des livres</i>.</p>
